lego:evidence  a  owl:AnnotationProperty .

gomodel:SYNGO_122  a      owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Three complementary methods were used to demonstrate that Bassoon regulates the number of calcium channels at the ribbon synapse. Immunofluorescence and STED microsopy demonstrated a reduced abundance of calcium channel signal at ribbons (Figure 2). electrophysiology and live imaging showed that this leads to a reduction of calcium influx (figure 3 and 4). Note that the mouse used in this study is only a partial knockout, and that a similar phenotype was observed in cultured neuron of a full knockout (Davydova et.al 2014).. Experimental description: Mice with deletion of exons 4 and 5 of the Bassoon gene (BsnΔEx4/5; Altrock et al., 2003) or carrying a gene-trapped allele (Bsngt, Lexicon Pharmaceuticals, Inc.), and wild-type littermates were used." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7620-2704" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1558-1958" ;
        dc:date           "2018-05-28" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_MF_122" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

